<subsection xml:id="subsec-finding-reciprocals-of-real-numbers-using-division">
    <title>Finding reciprocals of real numbers using division</title>
    <p>
     The reciprocal of a real number <m>x</m> is <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>, except when <m>x=0</m> since division by zero is undefined. 
    </p>
    <p>
        For example: the reciprocal of <m>2</m> is <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
     To find the reciprocal of <m>0.25</m> you first write the number as a fraction :<m>\frac{25}{100}</m>.
     Therefore, the reciprocal of <m>0.25 = \frac{100}{25}</m> which can be simplified to give <m>4</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        The reciprocal of <m>\frac{3}{5}</m> is <m>\frac{5}{3}</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{To find the reciprocal of a real number using division, follow these steps:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
       <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                 Understand the Reciprocal: The reciprocal of a real number <m>x</m> is <m>\frac{1}{x}</m>. 
                 This means that when you multiply a number by its reciprocal, the result is always <m>1</m>: 
              </p>
              <p>
                <md>
                    <mrow> x \times \frac{1}{x}=\amp 1</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Next, use division to find the reciprocal of a number.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Example: reciprocal of <m>5 = \frac{1}{5}</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Using division to find reciprocal of <m>5</m> we have:<m>1 \div 5 = 0.2</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    The reciprocal of <m>-3</m> is <m>1 div -3 = 0.333...</m> also written as <m>0.\dot{3}</m> to mean it is recurring.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol> 
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <ol marker= "1">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                          In groups of <m>5</m>, write down numbers from <m>2</m> to <m>15</m> in ascendinding order <m>(2,...,15)</m>.Label this as the first list.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Rearrange the numbers from <m>15</m> to <m>2</m> in descending order <m>(15, 14, 13, ..., 2)</m>. Label this as the Second List.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                           In turns, each group member to create a fraction by:

                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <ol marker="i)">
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                       Using the first number from the First List as the numerator.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Using the first number from the Second List as the denominator.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <p>
                                        Repeat the process until all numbers are used.
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ol>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Find the reciprocals of the fractions you have formed using division. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                           For example: Fractions formed are <m>\frac{2}{15},\frac{3}{14} , \frac{5}{12}, \frac{10}{7}, \frac{7}{10}</m>  then the reciprocal of <m>\frac{2}{15}</m> using division is <m>15 \div 2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Discuss your work with fellow learners.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
             Find the reciprocal of the following numbers using division.  
            </p>
            <p>
             <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                       <m>256</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>4.2</m> 
                    </p>
                </li>
             </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                          The reciprocal of <m>256</m> according to definition is <m>\frac{1}{256}</m> .
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Dividing it we have:
                        </p>
                         <tabular>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium"><m>0.003906</m></cell>
                                
                            </row>
                            <row> 
                                <cell right="medium"><m>256</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>1000</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium"><m>-768</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>2320</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>-</cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium" halign="center"><m>2304</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>1600</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>-</cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium" halign="center"><m>1536</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell halign="center"><m>64</m></cell>
                            </row>

                        </tabular>
                       
                        <p>
                            Hence, the reciprocal of <m>256</m> using division is <m>1\div 256 = 0.003906</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The reciprocal of <m>4.2</m> according to definition is <m>\frac{1}{4.2}</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            We can rerwrite <m>\frac{1}{4.2}</m> as <m> \frac{1}{4.2}\times \frac{10}{10} </m>
                            <md>                                                                  
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{10}{42} </mrow>
                                <mrow> =\amp \frac{5}{21} </mrow>
                            </md>
                        </p>
                        <p>
                        Dividing <m>21</m> by <m>5</m> we have:
                        </p>
                         <tabular>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium"><m>0.238</m></cell>
                                
                            </row>
                            <row> 
                                <cell right="medium"><m>21</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>50</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>-</cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium"><m>42</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell><m>80</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>-</cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium"><m>63</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell><m>170</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>-</cell>
                                <cell bottom="medium"><m>168</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell></cell>
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            </row>

                        </tabular>
                        <p>
                           Therefore, using division, the reciprocal of <m>4.2</m> is <m> 15\div 21 = 0.238</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
